item.title: As Coronavirus Restrictions Ease, People Slowly Emerge From Homes
item.description: As the U.S. monitors the tentative easing of lockdown measures, governments across Europe and Asia moved to further relax restrictions on business and social gatherings, even as new infections surged in some of the world’s largest developing countries.

item.title: Israel's High Court Hears Challenges to a Unity Government Led by Netanyahu
item.description: Prime Minister Netanyahu and his rival Benny Gantz have faced pushback from critics who say the deal shouldn’t leave Mr. Netanyahu in power while he faces bribery, fraud and breach of trust charges.

item.title: Filmmaker Jailed Over Music Video That Mocked Egypt's President Dies in Prison
item.description: An Egyptian filmmaker detained for two years over a music video that mocked Egypt President Abdel Fattah Al Sisi has died, another death inside the country’s prisons that human-rights groups have criticized for their harsh treatment of prisoners.

item.title: Parents of Slain Journalist Daniel Pearl Appeal Ruling That Would Free Accused
item.description: Ruth and Judea Pearl filed their petition at Pakistan’s top court to hear their appeal after the government of Pakistan also sought reinstatement of the original convictions in the case.

item.title: Italians Prepare to Return to Work, if They Can Find Child-Care
item.description: More than four million Italians are getting ready to go back to work in May after eight weeks of lockdown. But with schools and day-care centers closed until the fall, many parents are facing a dilemma: Who will look after the children?

item.title: Kim Jong Un, Smoking and Strolling, Reappears After Three-Week Absence
item.description: Newly published photo and video showed a smiling North Korean leader Kim Jong Un strolling around a factory Friday, ending a nearly three-week absence from public view that fueled rumors of his death.
